column1: 327025;instagram;2018-09-29 08:06:10;FALSE;#cw assault what happens when you tell all of the people that you are supposed to tell and no one helps you? when i was a minor i was hospitalized for depression. i told my then psychiatrist about my #sexualassault and he didn’t report my disclosure. by law he was supposed to report my disclosure to dcf within 48 hours. in my disclosure i mentioned it happened multiple times. i remember being too nervous to tell him exactly how many times it happened cuz i thought i somehow would get in trouble and i just said a few but it happened many more than that. i remember just wanting to go home so i tried to pretend like i was over it™️ i told him the boy who did it was my neighbor so he was aware the boy lived close to me...across the street to be exact. he knew my mother didn’t know about the assault. he didn’t even bother telling my mother even though i was going home on pass on weekends and that i was in danger of being assaulted again by the same boy. right now i’m posting my disclosure. i’m posting it because this was another day that unexpectedly changed my life. i’m posting it because when my doctor didn’t do anything after the disclosure i got scared and i completely shut down. i thought my rapist was right and it validated my fears and i thought that no one would ever believe me. it took years for me to talk about what actually happened. when i did finally tell people about what happened everyone was actually super supportive & it was like a weight had been lifted. my doctor was part of the reason #whyididntreport. it took me years to finally report my rape in part because of this doctor. i looked up my old doctor and he’s still practicing medicine. i just started the process of seeing if i can get his license revoked as what he did was illegal. i don’t want what happened to me to happen to anyone else. i’m taking the time to post my experience because i want anyone that may be struggling with everything that is going on in the news to know that you are powerful

column2: i can't help but feeling sympathy for this woman. a survivor of sexual assault and rape attempt
column3: a victim of drinking and rape culture
column4: she has suffered from trauma for nearly 40 years and had to have a couple therapy in 2012 with her husband. coming forwards against brett kavanaugh
column5: a nominee as a justice of us supreme court
column6: dr. ford has not much to gain yet everything to lose. but she decided to make her identity public. she was terrified and nervous and emotional through all the hearing. how can such person with all those signs could pass the polygraph test
column7: with the result sent to the washing post and us senate judiciary committee? because she was telling the truth. because she actually suffered from sexual assault and she was sure 100% that was brett kavanaugh. christine blasey ford took a polygraph test. brett kavanaugh didn't. she asked for an fbi investigation. he tried to avoid that. and yet
column8: the republican senators of the senate judiciary committee have made yesterday one of the saddest days for american women. a controversial nominee who has raised concern about the treatment of women
column9: about the appeal of roe v. wade
column10: who has the history of no vote to protect and improve the worsening condition of the environment
column11: brett kavanaugh is now facing three allegations of sexual harassment
column13: sexual abuse and rape attempt. but two of the accusers are ignored by the majority in the committee
column14: and the hearings of dr. ford showed the ugly face of the republicans. they rushed for the confirmation of brett kavanaugh
column15: the tried to defend him as much as possible
column16: they dismissed an fbi investigation which was the only way to find out the truth. a sad day for american justice
column17: the treatment of christine blasey ford
column18: in the wake of the #metoo movement
column19: was even worse than what happened to anita hill 27 years ago
column20: when her allegation was responded with an fbi investigation.

column1: نمایش فیلم «جاده قدیم» از چند روز پیش در سینماها آغاز شده است. منیژه حکمت به چند پرسش ما پاسخ داده است. (ورق بزنید) - «جاده قدیم» مال یکی‌دو سال اخیر نیست؛ پروسه‌ای ده ساله است.
- روی موضوع حساسی دست گذاشتم؛ اگر درست اجرا نمی‌شد می‌توانست به ضد خودش تبدیل شود.
- جنبش‌هایی نظیر #metoo باعث خوش‌حالی‌ست. امیدوارم در جامعه‌ ما هم رایج شود.
- مهتاب کرامتی یکی از بهترین بازی‌هایش را در «جاده قدیم» ارائه داده و طبق معمول حقش خورده شد.
- من خودم را سانسور نمی‌کنم ارشاد زحمتش را می‌کشد.
- همه‌چیز در هاله‌ای از سانسور است.حتا در زندگی مردم. ما به بدترین چیزها عادت کردیم. سانسور هم یکی از آن‌هاست.
- «لالایی» یکی از بهترین فیلم‌نامه‌هایی‌ست که من دارم و یک اتفاق است. امیدوارم روزی آن را بسازم.
- فضای سینما در دست نامحرمان است و به‌راحتی می‌گویند همه را می‌خریم.

column1: 327089;instagram;2018-09-29 06:42:05;FALSE;"trigger warning⚠️sexual assault⚠️ i’ve seen all of these brave individuals share their story so i decided to share mine.
when i was in high school i was having s really rough time
column2: between being in a very abusive relationship
column3: to losing a really good friend to suicide
column4: to almost taking my own life; one demon i never shared was the guy that was in one of my classes that forced me into his car and raped me during school hours
column5: he would constantly touch me in class and say horrid things
column6: even telling my boyfriend at the time that he would do it again. it’s destroyed my trust and has made it extremely hard to trust anyone. i didn’t really understand what was happening when it happened because i was never really taught about sexual assault and at the time i thought that’s what sex was
column7: but i hid it for a very long time until the end of the school year when i finally opened up to administration about it. they wouldn’t do anything. i suffered in silence because i thought everyone would think i was dirty and a whore. but as the years have gone on i’ve realized that i’m not the only one

column1: i've struggled all day with the decision to post something so private
column3: and so painful on social media. i am not looking for pity
column4: and i usually would not choose to write about this here
column5: but i feel like i have to do this
column6: to speak out against injustice with my own story.

column2: i was sexually assaulted for the first time. i was abused on a near daily basis for the next six years of my life in total silence. i told no one
column4: my closest friend and confidant who i knew was most likely going through the same thing. in some ways
column5: i was more afraid of the possible consequences of speaking up than i was of enduring- of continuing to run
column7: to seek shelter behind locked doors and in safe public spaces. even as a child
column8: i understood the injustice of the system. when i finally did speak
column9: i was removed from my home
column10: from the people who had raised me and loved me in order to ""protect"" me from my attacker
column11: while the man who had destroyed my life was sentenced to counseling. just counseling. nothing more. he is still in regular contact with young girls
column12: and his life was never torn apart the way mine was. i am so tired
column13: so sick of men not being held accountable for despicable behavior. for the love of the all too high percentage of people you likely know and care for who are survivors
column15: call your representatives and tell them to keep kavanaugh out of the supreme court. we do not need another man who will bring injustice to survivors in the court the way the court system had brought injustice to me when i was just a little girl.

column1: آزارهای جنسی به بالیوود رسید / افشاگری بازیگر زن

ایران آرت: تانوشری داتا، بازیگر و دختر شایسته کشور هند چندنفر از اهالی بالیوود از جمله نانا پاته‌کار و ویویک آگنیهورتی را به آزار جنسی متهم کرد. تعدادی از اهالی سینمای هند مانند پریانکا و پارینیتی چوپرا، فرهان اختر، توینکل خانا، ریچا چادا و سِوارا بسکار از این بازیگر حمایت کردند.

به گزارش دنیای تصویر آنلاین، نخستین بار تانوشری داتا در سال ۲۰۰۸ علیه نانا پاته‌کار،ویویک آگنیهورتی و چندنفر دیگر اتهاماتی را مطرح کرد اما او در گفتگویی اخیرا دوباره همان اتهامات را تکرار کرد که سبب شد این مساله دوباره موضوع روز شود. تانوشری داتا حتی در گفتگویش علتی  را که جنبش «من‌هم» در هند هیچ‌گاه به راه نخواهد افتاد،برشمرد.

فرهان اختر-کارگردان،تهیه کننده و بازیگر- که جنبش «مردان علیه هتک حرمت» را در هند راه انداخته از تانوشری داتا حمایت کرد و نوشت دلیل آنکه او ده سال تقریبا در محاق فراموشی مانده، مشخص است و جسارت او را ستود. پس از فرهان اختر تعدادی از چهره‌های سرشناس سینمای هند در شبکه‌های مجازی از او حمایت کردند.
اما ستارگان سینمای هند مانند آمیتاب باچان،امیرخان و سلمان خان در پاسخ به سوال خبرنگاران درباره اتهاماتی که تانوشری داتا مطرح کرده حاضر به جوابگویی نشدند

ایران آرت: تانوشری داتا، بازیگر و دختر شایسته کشور هند چندنفر از اهالی بالیوود از جمله نانا پاته‌کار و ویویک آگنیهورتی را به آزار جنسی متهم کرد. تعدادی از اهالی سینمای هند مانند پریانکا و پارینیتی چوپرا، فرهان اختر، توینکل خانا، ریچا چادا و سِوارا بسکار از این بازیگر حمایت کردند.

به گزارش دنیای تصویر آنلاین، نخستین بار تانوشری داتا در سال ۲۰۰۸ علیه نانا پاته‌کار،ویویک آگنیهورتی و چندنفر دیگر اتهاماتی را مطرح کرد اما او در گفتگویی اخیرا دوباره همان اتهامات را تکرار کرد که سبب شد این مساله دوباره موضوع روز شود. تانوشری داتا حتی در گفتگویش علتی  را که جنبش «من‌هم» در هند هیچ‌گاه به راه نخواهد افتاد،برشمرد.

فرهان اختر-کارگردان،تهیه کننده و بازیگر- که جنبش «مردان علیه هتک حرمت» را در هند راه انداخته از تانوشری داتا حمایت کرد و نوشت دلیل آنکه او ده سال تقریبا در محاق فراموشی مانده، مشخص است و جسارت او را ستود. پس از فرهان اختر تعدادی از چهره‌های سرشناس سینمای هند در شبکه‌های مجازی از او حمایت کردند.
اما ستارگان سینمای هند مانند آمیتاب باچان،امیرخان و سلمان خان در پاسخ به سوال خبرنگاران درباره اتهاماتی که تانوشری داتا مطرح کرده حاضر به جوابگویی نشدند

column1: 327100;instagram;2018-09-29 06:49:07;FALSE;"reading all the #whyistayed #metoo and now #whyididntreport stories tear my heart up every time. often because it makes me realize i have so many of my own. here’s a sample.
it was an accelerated high school science class: anatomy and physiology. and i was excited to have been accepted. i was about 16 or 17 and dressed in jeans
column3: purple chucks or black engineer boots
column4: and all the trappings of punk rock ie: spikes.

column1: the white male instructor immediately sexualized my appearance.

the comments escalated to asking questions about my body and who had access to it. ex: “how did you get that bruise? did someone take a bite out of you?”. the thing that made me report him is he said “why don’t you come over for private tutoring lessons in exchange for something like mowing my lawn or i’m sure you can think of something you’re better at” in front of other students. no one else said anything about it but they had witnessed it. i was humiliated but also angry. so angry.
i reported him to the school counselor.
the counselor got the loathsome creepy white male vice principal as well as my dad involved.
i was informed the teacher was going through a divorce and was having a really tough time.
their solution was allowing me to withdraw from the class without penalizing me.
there are so many other events that occurred at that age. i’m not even going to mention all the keggers. i grew up in a college town.
so i believe that everyone believes any survivor is believable.
keeping the status quo is the goal of patriarchy.
i had a psychology teacher say to the class “keep homosexuals out of my face
column2: why do they have to show off how disgusting they are”. i ended up dropping out of high school even though i had been accepted to the university of colorado. at 20
column3: while working at chuck e. cheese’s for $3.35/hour i earned my hs diploma at night school. and now my hands are shaking as i tap share.

column1: 327131;instagram;2018-09-29 06:17:06;FALSE;"“to partners of people with sexual trauma
hold your beloved. close and with care.
rest your ear to her heart. listen for its truth in speed and texture

column5: what does that part of you need to know
column7: how can i help you experience repair? – even if i wasn't the one who caused the pain. – even if i accidentally piled more on.

column1: give her space and presence and care
column3: until something exhales from the center of her pain. (non-poetically
column4: let there be quiet and breathing and no words.

column1: in the absence of your knowing what's going on for her
column2: everything is coming together under her skin.) hold your beloved like the god of redemption is sending light through your willing hands

column1: hold your beloved and let her cry and cry and cry

column5: you might feel the instinct to ask her if she could've done

column1: not had those drinks. not smoked that pot. not gone out looking for love or lust or good conversation.
not gotten a job. not gone to the party. not had a god forsaken female body.

column2: i beg of you – ask a different question:

column1: what's going on with the men? you might want to ask
column2: have you ever thought about reporting him?

column4: she'll tell you how horrible it was.

column2: i beg of you – ask a different question:

column1: how can i support you? hold your beloved. close and with care. rest your ear to her heart. listen for its truth.

column2: most important thing you can do.
put your own two hands on your very own heart and ask the god within
column3: ""where should i begin? use me move me make me a force for healing justice protection love."" listen. listen. listen.

column1: we need your hands and your heart
column2: your devotion to doing your part.

column1: i know you want to. i know the king in there is in despair. the real repair is rising.”

column3: and journey - hoping to give others the strength to come forward when they were ready. i chose to be open and honest knowing that at times it’d hurt my family. knowing that i’d lose people
column4: and i did. knowing that people wouldn’t understand and people would victim blame
column5: and they did. but here we are 2 years and 1 month later.  the abuse i experienced started when i was only 6 years old. a baby really. unable to understand what was happening
column6: and only able to understand what i was told. “if you say anything
column7: you’ll ruin the family”. i’ve lived in fear since i was a 6 year old little girl
column8: when i learned the world wasn’t a friendly place.

column1: 327172;instagram;2018-09-29 05:55:03;FALSE;"i am so tired of this world we live in. why did it take a political fight to raise awareness to sexual violence? why did it take a celebrity sexually assaulting a celebrity for a movement to be formed? why did someone famous have to drug and force himself on someone before the conversation was opened? more importantly
column2: why are victims at fault? why are victims getting the bad name?

column1: no one cares that a woman may have been sexually assaulted. they only care if she is democrat or republican. i would hope like hell that no person is evil enough to lie about such a thing.
it took me 6 years to tell. there i said it. i dealt with it for almost 6 years and not another soul on the planet knew what i was going through on an almost daily basis. mind you
column2: i was 8 when it started. not only did it take 6 years but it took another 8 before he was in prison. people think it is so easy to come forward and speak your truth but it's not that simple.

column1: he said he would kill me.
he said he would murder my family and make it look like an accident.
he said no one would believe me.

why else? i was embarrassed and afraid!! i didn't want anyone to know what happened to me. i didn't want to be treated differently. i didn't want to be a girl with ""problems"". why did i end up telling? because one day it got to be too much. one day he threw me down a bit too hard... one day i couldn't stand looking at myself in the mirror anymore.

if you haven't been through it... you really don't understand. we all have stories we will never tell. this has nothing to do with politics and i can care less what side you are on. i hate that being a ""victim"" or having ""ptsd"" has been turned into some joke to people. this is my every. day. life... not a prime time news story.

column2: that is my vent. take it or leave it.

column1: 327186;instagram;2018-09-29 05:59:32;FALSE;"i’ve spend the last few days either attempting to hide from the current news cycle or feeling very ill about it and how polarized our society is. today i realized that the whole thing - both the immediate drama and the encompassing treatment of women by those in power - reminds me of the cycle of abuse. i remember first learning about this cycle my sophomore year of college in women’s studies 101. i am fortunate to have never experienced it intimately firsthand but over the years i’ve seen it again and again in the lives of women close to me and of those i barely know. again and again. trauma repeating itself throughout history and institutions and the powerful. trauma that damages and restricts all of humanity.

column2: sitting in that women’s studies course in kane hall
column3: felt more hopeful than i do now. but then i viewed the cycle of abuse in context of a singular relationship
column4: not our country’s culture and approach to women who have been abused and taken advantage of.

column1: 327218;instagram;2018-09-29 05:39:05;FALSE;"the first time i was sexually assaulted i was 6. it was by another child. i didn’t report it because i didn’t think kids could hurt each other like that. the second time i was sexually assaulted
column2: i was walking two blocks from my house to the local farmers market. a man pulled up in a car next to me with his privates exposed
column3: and asked me to watch him fondle himself. when i said no
column4: he reached to grab my arm and i ran. i was 10. i reported this one
column5: but the police decided i  as too young to give a proper physical description and dropped it. the third time i was sexually assaulted i was with my best friend in a surf shop on main street looking at swimsuits. a man came up close behind us and said

column1: allow yourself to relax. breathe deeply and retreat into yourself. become aware of your body; are you tense? in pain? is it easy to breathe deeply or does your body resist? do your thoughts flow easily or jump around? do sounds seem louder and more harsh than they normally do? are you more sensitive to light?

column2: a place or a color that soothes you
column4: examine its details and explore your thoughts again. are you still as tense? has your breathing changed? are you able to focus better? stay with the image/color/place for a few minutes and then try another. repeat this process and then check in with yourself again
column5: each time allowing your mind to go wherever it needs to. don’t push thoughts away even if they are unpleasant
column6: just let them roll through your mind
column7: becoming aware of any shifts. just keep focusing on the image
column8: the colors and the details...give it a try and let me know how you feel afterward.

column1: i’m not going to put my experience or story into words. i’m not going to try to convince people sexual assault is bad. cause if you need me to spell that out for you it’s not my job. it’s not my job as a survivor to educate everyone around me
column2: i will try to do that -but it’s my main job to survive. and support other survivors. as hard as it is
column3: i’m focusing on just that right now. today i couldn’t have these conversations. that’s valid
column4: that’s real. i stand with survivors. you are strong
column8: and please be light on your heart. take your time
column10: and remember your trauma is yours and no one else can tell you what to do with it. this week has been so so heavy for me and so many others but i’m here if anyone needs to talk.

column1: 327310;instagram;2018-09-29 04:41:39;FALSE;"i'm so bothered by what's happening in the world right now.

here's a shot of my steel toes from yesterday's site meeting. the meeting where i was the only female among 8+ men. where i felt momentarily anxious about walking into the old boys club and knew some of them believed that i didn't even belong there.

this was 2 days after my women's group was confronted by the dean of our business school and told that we should take a more 'feminist' approach to our events because one with ww may be seen as offensive.
today was the day that i argued with a friend about how women need to be heard. whether their truth is being spoken now or 30 years from now.
i saw a post on instagram yesterday that struck me. nobody has ever questioned the men that came forward about being victimized by priests 20 or 30 years ago.
we're at a turning point in history with the current #metoo and #timesup movements. it's our time. our turn.

column2: and we deserve the level of equality and respect that our counterparts have never had to work for.

as a survivor of sexual assault
column2: i’m feeling all the feelings right now. rage. sadness. disbelief. rage. numbness. cynicism. triggered af. white hot rage. it feels like our stories don’t matter
column4: because even when one of us gets up and bravely delves into every tiny detail of what happened for hours on end in front of millions of people
column5: it’s not enough to sway the men in power. and truly
column6: we *don’t* matter to those men; we never did. the only thing that matters to them is holding onto their power and privilege—including power over the bodies of women and other marginalized people—and accumulating more of it.

column1: but even if we don’t matter to them
column2: we still matter to the world. we still matter to anyone with a moral compass
column3: a shred of decency. we still matter to history. because generations from now
column4: people are going to look back and see this and the whole #metoo and #timesup movement as a turning point
column5: a moment when a powerful wave of survivors shook off the shame and rose up to tell our stories. the first woman president of the united states
column7: was watching those hearings and feeling a growing call to action. the stories that survivors have been telling these past few years matter. we still matter. you still matter.

column1: so please take care of yourself
column2: and treat yourself like you matter. you deserve to eat
column5: to leave the house if you feel ready. you deserve to lie in bed all day if that’s what you need. and then
column7: you deserve to take to the streets in protest
column8: and to fight back at the polls in november. you deserve to have your voice heard
column9: because it matters. you deserve to take up space

column1: 327369;instagram;2018-09-29 01:17:46;FALSE;"this is what a woman that has been raped looks like... written by ricardo ramirez
would you have ever guessed she was sexually assaulted by seeing this photo? probably not. just because we don’t physically see someone being sexual assaulted
column2: does not mean it did not happen. last year my wife was sexually assaulted in riverside ca. it happened 4 months after i proposed to her
column3: and went to court and faced her assailant 1 month after our wedding day. no one knew what we went through the last year and a half. no one knows of the long crying nights
column7: and triggers that we dealt all while trying to “host” a wedding. yesterday i watched dr. fords testimony of her sexual assault and i felt her pain since my wife has experienced sexual assault her self. and to hear the way kavanaugh and the senator respond is fucking disgusting. sexual assault is not something that happens one night and you forget about it. it completely changes your life
column8: and will be part of your life till you die. some days it’s like day 1 all over again. the memories are vivid
column10: police station is still chillingly cold
column12: small actions and memories are intense triggers. when she was assaulted
column13: i couldn’t even hug or comfort my wife because her clothing and fingernails had evidence that the police needed to collect
column14: and me comforting her would be tampering evidence. this is our story from a normal wednesday night turned into a nightmare.

column1: we don’t want pity. we want awareness for sexual assault. if you have been a victim of sexual assault. please speak to someone you trust or seek a therapist that specializes in sexual assault. my wife has done therapy every week since her assault
column2: and it has helped her more than anything.

column1: we cannot allow this to keep happening!!
if you know someone that is a victim of sexual assault
column2: please be a friend to them and ask them how they are really doing. sharing is healing. men
column3: thank you for doing your part to protect woman and give them a shoulder to cry on or a ear that’s willing to listen.

column2: i hear you and i believe you. you have given so many women courage

column1: i was 17 and i t was my manager
column2: a man twice my age with a wife and children. drunk one night he cornered me in the storage closet asking me to kiss him. i told him no
column3: at first i thought he was joking
column4: but i quickly realized he wasn’t and i panicked that my words might not be enough. i was saved by customers walking by laughing on the other side of the wall
column5: their presence and the open door must have scared him
column6: so i ran out of there and back to my work station where i thought i was safe. it wasn’t even two minutes before he was behind me kissing my neck. he took what he wanted
column7: he ignored my words and pretended like nothing happened. when i finally spoke out and tried to hold him accountable the owner of the restaurant
column8: an expectant mother and successful restauranteur
column9: called me a liar. she told me that he was an upstanding man with a family and would never do that
column10: she hen accused me of poor job performance. my mother
column12: sprung into action when i told her what had happened. she told me we could go to court
column13: but the thought of telling my story all over again
column14: was too much. the courage dr ford has showed and continues to demonstrate is powerful
column16: and i believe her. thank you for giving me the courage to share and in doing so the chance to not carry this alone.

column1: 327420;instagram;2018-09-29 03:56:42;FALSE;"i was sexually assaulted when i was in college. in this country we don't talk openly about such things. these conversations need to happen. i ended up telling my female psychology professor what had happened and she didn't instruct me to file a report
column2: she was kind and compassionate but her only advice was to find a counselor and a support group. i don't care what your political leanings are. this tweet is ignorant
column4: and insulting. what happened to me happened in 1998 and i still wasn't encouraged to go to the police! i also didn't tell my parents what happened to me until 2008! sexual assault should be taken seriously people! i happen to be a person who would happily vote for a worthy republican. a person who is also sickened that a man who bragged on tape about sexual assault (""just grab them by the pussy"") and had nearly 20 credible sexual assault allegations brought against him
column5: sits in our highest office. it's time we take this shit seriously! maybe i shouldn't get political on social media but this is way bigger than politics. it's about being humans and looking after our fellow humans and also holding them accountable for wrong doings! i won't apologize about starting a dialogue that we need to have. #rapesurvivor #metoo #disgrace #discussion #brettkavanaugh #christineblaseyford #dialogue #talk #sexualassault #noshame #proudsurvivor #timeforchange #notmypresident";;en;#RapeSurvivor

column1: 327432;instagram;2018-09-29 03:59:54;FALSE;let me just be extra real. this has been a rough stretch for me. rough for lots of people on top of my own struggles too. so we ran away for a recharge. and it was bliss. but it also showed me just how exhausted i am. all. the. time. and we came back to the two most charged days of this confirmation process that is very triggering and raw and hurting me at my core. because i don't carry a story. i carry stories. i don't have one #metoo  moment
column2: i have a lifetime of events. and i'm carrying them with generational stories
column3: and stories from almost every woman i consider a close friend. i knew this was going to be a tough week. to try and stay in a place of grounded gratitude i put sand from the beach in my shoes. and these last couple days i've walked with the sand in my toes. giving myself a physical reminder of the beauty that is in the world too. reminding myself to breathe deep. to listen to my own self care needs. and that the world will keep shifting under my feet
column4: but i am developing a strong

column1: 327434;instagram;2018-09-29 04:00:29;FALSE;"it’s time for courageous chick of the week!
each week we honour one iconic courageous chick who helped to change the world
column2: in the hope of inspiring other women to do the same.

column1: today is the 84th birthday of french actress

column2: bardot became an icon in the 50s and 60s for her roles in classic movies ‘and god created women’ and ‘contempt.’ however
column3: her first dream was to become a ballet dancer
column4: and she studied at the national superior conservatory of paris during her youth. she appeared on the cover of french elle at the tender age of 15
column5: but it was a few years before bardot was discovered by filmmaker roger vadim
column6: who also became her husband. ‘and god created women’ was vadim’s directorial debut
column7: but it was bardot who the movie launched to international stardom. off-screen bardot’s natural beauty led to her sexual symbol status
column8: which was described as embodying the french concept of “joie de vivre.” however
column9: fame was too much for bardot to handle
column10: and she attempted suicide on her 26th birthday. she survived
column11: and would later describe how the pressures of celebrity life and the need to maintain a certain image had worn her down.

column1: bardot retired from acting in the 1970s to become an animal rights activist. she founded the foundation for the protection of distressed animals
column2: which led to the council of europe stopping seal fur imports and the french government banning ivory imports.
in recent years bardot has become somewhat of a controversial figure
column3: both for her racist remarks and for calling the #metoo movement “hypocritical.” but at least fans can remember and still be inspired by her golden age
column4: as well as her work to protect the rights of animals.

column2: and re entered the art world unintentionally... i refused to sell anything for a year and just needed to create for me.. i just needed to purge. i left art over 10 years ago ..and this was my first piece back was.. a self portrait. based on what others or ..the people that assaulted me (as a sober woman by means of ghb.. ) this is how i think they viewed me. and this is me looking at that perception. it’s dangerous for us... 1:6  1 out of 6.. women.. trying to harness or take the essence of a women.. without her choosing you.. i symbolized it like strawberry water... it taste like a strawberry.. but it’s not the real thing... and they will never know passion. only greed. i feel empowered now.. i’m picky. but it’s my choice.. this is the first time i’ve gone public about that... i turned my lemons into lemonade.. and now in october my first installation is inside an established a museum.... lemonade. but accepting #kavanaugh ...you’re telling all women in america

column1: 327472;instagram;2018-09-29 03:42:22;FALSE;"how can men become allies in the #metoo movement and advocates for #genderequality? find out at the ""unpacking masculinity"" workshop featured at the 30th annual women's leadership conference on friday

column1: 327476;instagram;2018-09-29 03:43:04;FALSE;"i've had so many conversations around this trial the past few days. a coworker of mine said she was mad. i wish i were angry
column2: but i'm sad. another female told me of the first time she was sexually assaulted. i stopped her and asked if she heard what she had just said
column4: not the one time. i remember my first time. i was 11. it was the only one i reported. i'm sad that women experience sexual assault at such an alarming rate that most of us have experienced it more than once. i'm sad that i have friends that witnessed my sexual assault when i was 19 and not one of them has reached out to see if i'm okay. luckily
column5: i don't need them to reach out
column6: but it's the thought that matters. if you have a friend or family member that you know has been sexually assaulted
column7: please check on them. hearing someone else's story can be a trigger. one thing i am glad of is that women are feeling empowered to come forward and tell their stories. thank you anita hill for being at the grassroots of this movement. .

column2: my head is swirling with what all this kavanaugh & dr. ford situation is bringing about. there is so much to digest. so many angles and perspectives to take in. so many conversation to have and so many changes to be made.

column1: i don't often share my opinions about heated topics because it doesn't feel safe for me to do so. i'm not interested in being traumatized or retraumatized after all the healing and forgiveness work i've done over the past several years. i'm more interested in investing my time & energy in collectively moving into a space of love.
one of the hardest things for me to watch is how cruel people are to each other when they are posting their opinions

column2: a person makes a comment with their observation and opinion and gets attacked by hundreds of people on instagram.

column1: the attackers say mean & hurtful things that they likely wouldn't say to the person if they stood in front of them and looked them in the eyes and saw them as a human being instead of a social media profile.
or if a person is upset with kavanaugh
column3: or trump and they say very unkind things on facebook about them and sometimes share the most unflattering image they could find.

column2: we all have our opinions. we all have our pasts
column4: and therefore biases that have us react

column2: before you react or rant or share unflattering things about others on social media remember these things:

column1: 1) just because you have an opinion doesn't mean you're right.
2) whatever you say and everything you say is reflective of you
3) we are all humans trying to do the best we can with what we know
4) kindness goes a long way and can completely turn a situation around.
5) your reaction has something to do with your past and there is some work you must do to heal it and gain the wisdom from it. ""memory without emotional charge is wisdom."" dr. joe dispenza
6) today is a great day to choose love.
if it makes just one person stop and think before they post

column1: i am a sexual assault survivor.

column2: raped and abused for years as a child
column3: which was only the tip of the “sexual assault iceberg” i would endure in my life.

column1: even up to just a few months ago.
i didn’t talk about it for decades and i do not want to talk about it now.
this kind of trama cuts too deep!
if you have never lived through this
column2: than you can not even imagine how any of us who have

column1: there isn’t a day that goes by that i’m not scared for my daughter.
worried that any male adult she comes in contact with may have been inappropriate with her.
i’ve had numerous conversations with them about her safety.
and these were because of my fears and my past.
i will not always be able to protect my daughter
but i will make damn sure that her voice will be heard.
that her body will be protected.
that i understand staying silent and all of the reasons behind it
but that i hope if something like this ever happens to her or friend or if she ever even hears whispers of something like this in her life
column2: that she can come to me and i will believe her.

column1: and if she is going through it
column2: i will never make a deadline for her to express her pain and anger.
i don’t have a deadline either.
i am not ready yet to share my story.
because it is just too much. . * i ask that you respect my candid honesty. i do not need anyone to comment.  this is already a sensitive subject. and
column3: i’m ok. there is no need for worry. but i urge you to check in with your people. unless you’ve been through this
column4: then you have zero understanding how this is affecting them.*

each day i get to work with young ladies in this age group and i’m humbled by the things i learn. i see how beautiful
column3: and how captivating each and every one of them is. i deeply feel how fragile
column5: and how delicate they are. i’ve learned that no matter how big or small
column6: every human interaction has such a powerful effect on them. that every good thing is not good enough for them
column7: yet the smallest negative experience can be crucial to them. that they demand through their words and actions how much they look up to adults around them. that i can only oblige to fulfill that demand
column8: especially knowing that things they go through and emotions they deal with are not any less smaller than what any adult faces
column9: if not bigger. i didn’t know about the kind of helplessness i would face in teaching until i started. and guilt in seeing them persevere and still smile while i can’t do anything for them.

column1: 327512;instagram;2018-09-29 03:28:52;FALSE;"i bought my first piece of jewelry when i sophomore in college. it was a gold ring with two onyx stones. it was something like $200
column2: which was a goddamn fortune to me. i bought it
column3: and i wore it for ten years
column4: even after the stones were scratched and the soft metal of the band bent in more than one place.

column2: and a talisman. it was the only way i could take the blackness i felt in my heart
column3: and contain it outside of my body. that ring was was how i survived the aftermath of my rape.

column1: i didn't report what happened to me. i could barely even process what happened to me. like every other young woman i knew - and every woman i've known since - i understood that my body did not belong to me. i understood that boundaries only existed for me when the men around me chose to recognize and enforce them. at 19 years old
column2: rape was just the capstone to years of unwanted comments

column1: i'm 45 years old now. i'm tall
column5: and i lead a privileged and comfortable life. i go to work every day at a giant fortune 500 company
column6: populated by an heavily male workforce. and i recognize every single day that i struggle to avoid eye contact in the hallway. because i still know the rules. i still know that eye contact
column8: that a simple choice can be read as an invitation
column9: or something more. because i'm a woman.

column1: because this is the reality of life as a woman.

327525;instagram;2018-09-29 03:05:01;FALSE;"carrying a very heavy heart tonight as i am forced to reflect on the realities of sexual violence against women in our society.

as i watched countless men babble about all the ways this allegation has affected them negatively without stopping to breathe and consider the absolutely devastating impact this moment has had on this woman’s life
column2: or the astounding courage it must have taken to risk her safety and well-being to speak about this traumatic time. i am again reminded of the incredible bravery and strength of women as i read the heart breaking stories of sexual abuse my friends and acquaintances have shared on social media today that have also forced me to recall similar experiences in my past.

column1: it is never to late to tell the truth. it is never too late to hold people responsible. and it is never too late to decide to stop brushing off the problem and making excuses for the disgusting patterns of behavior in our society. if you are a woman
column2: thank you for sharing your stories if you have
column3: or thank you for supporting your fellow women who have chosen to share. if you are a man
column4: hold your fellow man to the same standards you conduct yourself with and speak up if you hear or see something that perpetuates this toxic pattern of sexually predatory behavior. no matter who/what you are
column5: we should all be looking out for the safety and health of our fellow human
column6: not looking to break them down or take what is not ours to take.

i draw a line down the middle of a chalkboard
column2: sketching a male symbol on one side & a female symbol on the other.

column1: then i ask just the men: what steps do you guys take
column3: to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally
column4: a young a guy will raise his hand and say
column5: 'i stay out of prison.' this is typically followed by another moment of laughter
column6: before someone finally raises his hand & soberly states

column1: then i ask the women the same question. what steps do you take on a daily basis to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? women throughout the audience immediately start raising their hands. as the men sit in stunned silence
column2: the women recount safety precautions they take as part of their daily routine.

column1: hold my keys as a potential weapon. look in the back seat of the car before getting in. carry a cell phone. don't go jogging at night. lock all the windows when i sleep
column2: even on hot summer nights. be careful not to drink too much. don't put my drink down and come back to it; make sure i see it being poured. own a big dog. carry mace or pepper spray. have an unlisted phone number. have a man's voice on my answering machine. park in well-lit areas. don't use parking garages. don't get on elevators with only one man
column3: or with a group of men. vary my route home from work. watch what i wear. don't use highway rest areas. use a home alarm system. don't wear headphones when jogging. avoid forests or wooded areas
column4: even in the daytime. don't take a first-floor apartment. go out in groups. own a firearm. meet men on first dates in public places. make sure to have a car or cab fare. don't make eye contact with men on the street. make assertive eye contact with men on the street ― jackson katz

column1: 327615;instagram;2018-09-29 02:40:47;FALSE;i am tired. it’s been an emotionally draining week. this is a confusing time in our country with lots of mixed messages going around and our kids need to hear from parents a loud and clear message of what is and isn’t ok. if you have a young boy
column4: today is a good day to talk about consent with them. even if you’re sure they would never take advantage of someone. have the talk anyway. have it again. even if it’s awkward. especially if it’s awkward. keep talking about it until it’s not awkward. they need to hear from you that it is unequivocally not ok to take advantage of someone
column5: especially when alcohol is involved. if they see someone trying to take advantage of a girl who has been drinking
column6: they need to step in and say something. that “no” and “stop” mean exactly that. i plan on raising this boy to help dismantle the rape culture all around us. he will know that “locker room banter” is not ok but demeaning to women and to those who engage in it. i will teach him empathy
column7: compassion and respect for his fellow human beings. #rapeculture is not a women’s issue. we can’t just teach girls not to be raped. we have to lay the groundwork early to raise boys who understand boundaries and decency and that it’s ok to be afraid and show weakness. that masculinity doesn’t just mean being tough. i love this boy and i love my daughter and all of our sons and daughters deserve a better world. it’s up to us to help them change it. #raisethemright;;en;#rapeculture

column1: 327629;instagram;2018-09-29 01:09:45;FALSE;"i would like to take a moment to thank our advocates. to all of those that believed us when we say something didn’t feel right. because usually that’s all we have to go on at first - a feeling.
thank you for not needing details of exactly what happened to know we aren’t lying. thank you for standing up for our truth and going to bat for us when we are too young
column3: too unsure to go to bat for ourselves. thank you for supporting us years later when we continue to deal with the ways our trauma and truth have shaped both our strengths and cracks in our survivor’s armor.

column10: strangers on the street and internet who are cut from similar cloth: thank you.

column1: thank you from the bottom of my heart. without you
column2: many of us would probably not be here today. without you
column3: we would be far more stuck in fear than we probably are today.

column1: 327647;instagram;2018-09-29 02:28:35;FALSE;"this was the cry of a guy as i tried to explain to him that his comments were part of the problem within rape culture. this was his statement as he tried to explain to me why dr. ford couldn't possibly be telling the truth. this was his declaration as he told me what a victim would and wouldn't remember in traumatizing circumstances. this is what he said after stating that false allegations would ruin the #metoo movement.

what he fails to understand is no amount of ""man-splaining"" is going to make the details from an event over 30 years ago line up exactly the way he thinks it should. what he doesn't understand is that beating a woman down for coming forward is what happens the majority of the time
column2: not every so often. what he's missing is that every person deals with trauma differently. what he doesn't get is that there wouldn't have to be a #metoo movement if women were treated on the regular with any type of respect
column3: if woman didn't have to think about the blow back. if more rapists were prosecuted. if other people weren't more concerned about the man's future than the women's.

column1: what needs to be understood is that you can't ""be against rape"" and then constantly defend and make excuses for perpetrators. you can't ""be against rape"" and not believe a woman because she can't produce an exact timeline along with diagrams and charts of the attack. you can't ""be against rape"" while deciding what should and shouldn't be remembered.
i'm not saying false allegations don't happen. what i'm saying is that those few cases shouldn't and wouldn't invalidate the real ones if we simply believed women. #believewomen";;en;#metoo

column3: a slayer of words and truths and myths
column4: there is always a story to tell. there is always a life to recount and a yarn to spin
column5: every thread hanging on a mind frayed from ceaseless

column2: chaotic circus that contains universes within grains of thought

column1: the bigger picture always comes into view when we take a step back and broaden our perspective. when we finally admire it for once rather than obsessing over every speck as it nervously climbs the four walls of consciousness.
what i'm saying is that my internal world never rests
column3: never stops creating as sparks scatter into ash.

column2: i sift and wrestle and struggle and labor over ideas and images just as the artist considers its canvas
column3: just as the sculptor reckons with the marble and coaxes it to life.

column1: it's the tension of knowing what to say and how and when to say it. of always having something to share but deciding as to what is most appropriate and relevant and true. of settling on a particular song but changing the timbre entirely.
of insisting on my own voice but
column3: offering one that has yet to be heard.

column1: so i damn my own privilege to spew and spit and scream whatever i want without recourse
column2: that i represent a culture that continues to discredit the accuser rather than the accused
column3: to shame the abused rather than the abuser
column4: to silence the oppressed rather than the oppressor.

column1: that i still dream and hope and raise children within constructs where it is advantageous to have a penis
column2: even more so if you're of a lighter skin tone.

column1: i guess we can argue and ignore and rewrite history as we would prefer to remember it
column2: but we shouldn't act surprised when it still repeats itself.

column2: “why does it take so long for victims to speak up” because they don’t understand. it is the fear that those who are suppose to help them won’t stand up for them
column3: they think how it will affect their family and how they will be the ones bullied. all those thoughts that go through victims heads. that is being shown today and that is exactly why it takes so long for a victim to say something. the bullying must stop now
column4: we need to come together and show love and support and make a change starting right now!

column1: i want to be as open as i can not for myself but to help anyone else who needs to speak up. from the age of 12 until right before i turned 18 i was sexually abused by my coach/teacher. when i was in 11th grade students started to find out and before you knew it the entire school and town was talking. i had never felt so alone and scared in my life and i didn’t trust a single person to speak to. i never wanted to step foot in that school again and all i wanted was for my life to end. i dropped out of the public school that same year and home schooled myself so i could finish the rest of my junior and senior year. i was scared to death to open my mouth and i kept quite until i was 20 i finally got the courage to go to the police and speak up. the investigation and trial was definitely scary and as you can imagine very emotional but i stayed strong and fought and he was sentenced 15 years.

column2: stand together and help other victims have the strength and courage to speak up for themselves and also to help others from becoming a victim in sexual abuse!❤️

column1: 327732;instagram;2018-09-28 00:35:17;FALSE;"today a very brave woman said “he didn’t rape me so i thought i should just move on” a phrase that has crossed my mind hundreds of times. it’s served to illegitimate my trauma
column2: to make excuses for the man who tried to gaslight me into thinking he
column4: would never disrespect a woman like that. i have spent the last few years since telling myself that it wasn’t my fault but never really believing it. i have believed every brave woman who has opened up to me about her sexual assault or harassment but i have not been as compassionate with myself. today watching dr blasey ford was inspiring and absolutely infuriating
column5: but it reminded me that we must not only believe each other but also ourselves. we must trust ourselves enough to be firm in our convictions even when the world uses its tricks to discredit our trauma.dr ford has proven that no matter how credible of a source you are or how perfect your recall is there will be people who won’t believe you. they will make the personal political and pretend your pain was created to further a political agenda. these people prevailed when anita hill spoke her truth and we must make sure that this time we are louder. this time we will believe each other. this time we will speak up and believe in ourselves. please reach out if you ever need support or just someone to listen. also the link in my bio is a video where many brave women share their stories.

column1: 327737;instagram;2018-09-29 01:48:02;FALSE;"i was the girl in this picture the first time i was raped.
i did not kick and scream.
i did not bite and scratch.
i did not beg and plead.
i. did. not. say. no. when. i. was. raped!
does that mean i wanted it to happen?
does that mean my anti-father had every right to force himself on me in a jealous rage?
were my silent tears an insufficient form of protest?
it's funny the details you remember
column2: and what gets foggy with time. i now can't remember if i was 10 or 11 the first time he actually forced me to have sexual intercourse with him. .

column1: i know i was very close to 11. i know it was spring but i can't pinpoint the exact month anymore. i remember it all happened so fast. .
he was accusing me of having sex with boys in my 5th-grade class. the next thing i knew i was being forced to have sex with a 40 something-year-old man who was supposed to love me as a daughter. .
a man who claimed to be my father
column2: not my stepfather. a man who's role was to protect  me from the evils of the world
column3: was the evil in my world. to this day he remains the person who has hurt me most in my life.

column1: that was only the first time he raped me. it happened over and over again as had the molestation that predated the rape by years.

i got to thinking about this today because over the last several weeks the bill cosby and the kavanaugh accusations have involved me in some horrifying conversations. i've been personally attacked by rape apologists who blame and shame victims.
ones where i am constantly reminded that society puts the burden of proof on the victim of rape along with the responsibility to prevent the rape from occurring.

column2: what could i have done differently? ++should i have fought harder?

column1: do you honestly think any of those things would have changed the outcome?
i ask you to consider all of this the next time you learn about a woman being raped. rape doesn't look like it does on tv most of the time. a lot of time there isn't a struggle only a surrender. .
there often isn't a no nor is there a uncoerced yes. .

column4: 30 + years to come forward with a sexual assault accusation and you know what in some cases never at all. i personally have experienced it twice by people who i thought i could trust who i imagined knew what no means no. i was so young at the time and so naive that for years i thought it was my fault. men need to realize that no means no
column5: just because she says yes and is an inebriated state it still means no. it is a scary time to be a woman when we can’t even speak our truth without passing judgement or humiliation.

column1: 327755;instagram;2018-09-29 01:52:20;FALSE;"昨日はリボンの会、リースの会でした。
たくさんの涙と勇気と混乱を見ました。 「少しずつ、自分を責める気持ちを薄くして歩いて行きたいです」
居なくなりたいと言ってた彼女が最後に伝えてくれました。
傷つけた人が悪いのであって、あなたは何も悪くない。
この先、、自分が嫌になったり、おかしいと思ったら、それは被害の後遺症です。
この被害を自分の手でコントロールする事が一番大切です。
今は、否認や恐怖を感じているかもしれません。
無力だっただけで、何も悪くない。
あなたは大切な存在です。
ゆっくり休んで歩いていきましょう。
辿り着いてくれてありがとう。

column1: it has never been about the credibility of women.
dr. christine blasey ford withstood an impossible degree of scrutiny to prove to the world that kavanaugh
column2: the man seeking a lifetime appointment in the supreme court (highest court in the land)
column3: had sexually assaulted her in high school.

column1: dr blasey ford is from the same elite society as brett kavanaugh. but it wasn’t enough. to america
column2: her power is only diminished by an unfortunate circumstance of gender. to be ‘credible’ as a woman is still considered less than an untrustworthy

column1: dr. blasey ford has been courageous and despite the disgusting response from the gop and many from the right
column2: she is hailed as a hero among the political left.

law professor anita hill also courageously testified during a supreme court confirmation process. she made it clear that judge clarence thomas had sexually harassed her and acted on her civic duty to tell the truth. anita hill was not considered ‘credible’
column3: nor was she embraced by the political left. she was attacked and vilified across the country. were it not for women like anita hill
column4: we would not have movements like #metoo now.

column1: we must shift our need to sacrifice certain women so that others can be empowered. this isn’t when we give up
column2: it’s when we learn and grow and do things differently.
i have no doubt. but i want to remind y’all that this does not mean we lost the fight. on the contrary
column3: the real fight is just getting started. there will always be men like kavanaugh and his enablers in the pipeline and at the end of it
column5: a powerful force of women to stop them. every time we fight

column3: you are not alone! don’t ever let anyone put fear in you to stay quite. it is horrible to see how dr. ford and other victims of abuse have to fight so hard to be heard and are being bullied by others. i hope this does not put any fear in other victims to speak up but to encourage them and give them more strength to stand up for themselves.

column2: “why does it take so long for victims to speak up” because they don’t understand. it is the fear that those who are suppose to help them won’t stand up for them
column3: they think how it will affect their family and how they will be the ones bullied. all those thoughts that go through victims heads. that is being shown today and that is exactly why it takes so long for a victim to say something. the bullying must stop now
column4: we need to come together and show love and support and make a change starting right now!

column1: i want to be as open as i can not for myself but to help anyone else who needs to speak up. from the age of 12 until right before i turned 18 i was sexually abused by my coach/teacher. when i was in 11th grade students started to find out and before you knew it the entire school and town was talking. i had never felt so alone and scared in my life and i didn’t trust a single person to speak to. i never wanted to step foot in that school again and all i wanted was for my life to end. i dropped out of the public school that same year and home schooled myself so i could finish the rest of my junior and senior year. i was scared to death to open my mouth and i kept quite until i was 20 i finally got the courage to go to the police and speak up. the investigation and trial was definitely scary and as you can imagine very emotional but i stayed strong and fought and he was sentenced 15 years.

column2: stand together and help other victims have the strength and courage to speak up for themselves and also to help others from becoming a victim in sexual abuse!❤️

column1: 327768;instagram;2018-09-29 00:58:40;FALSE;"@calgaryherald • this is the face of a calgary high school sexual assault victim. this is the face of a woman who was told that charges could not be laid in her case based on the presence of underage drinking. this is the face of a woman who experienced a similar incident to dr. christine blasey ford in an urban area outside of calgary in the province of alberta/canada in may 2008. this is the face of a local sexual assault victim who was bullied mercilessly by her peers in her senior year of high school after an evil incident occurred that she did not warrant. this is the face of a young teenage girl who can say with 100% certainty that she did not give consent to her assailants. this is the face of a daughter who hid the truth from her family and friends because she wasn’t only embarrassed... she was afraid; of her single mother blaming herself for not protecting her daughter
column2: of her younger sister no longer seeing her as a role model and of what her community would think if the truth came out. this is the face of indelible perseverance
column3: courage and strength despite immense suffering endured in the last 10 years. this is the face of a warrior and i dare you to tell me that the pain i still experience is not valid and the trauma i still re-live is not real. for you to publish a column that was meant to silence and strike fear in to the women in our city
column6: in our world like me... is absolutely deplorable. shame on you for hiding behind your right to “free speech”. you clearly do not know the difference between what is “free” and what is “damaging”. i call on you to stand with local victims and victims everywhere to right your wrongs before you do further damage to your reputation in your pathetic attempt to keep us quiet - #thebohowolfmommy —> #calgaryherald #calgaryrapeculture #naomilakritz #poorjournalism #boycottcalgaryherald #rapeculture #normalisingrapeculture #calgary #calgarycrime #alberta #albertacrime #ibelieveher #ibelievechristineblaseyford #rageagainstthedyingofthelight #yyc #yycnow #yycliving #calgaryliving #endrapeoncampus #nomeansno #assaultisassault #rapeisrape #metoo #believesurvivors #believewomen #imasurvivor";;en;#thebohowolfmommy

column3: it couldn’t have been as bad as it was. i didn’t tell anyone. the daily bouts of crying and inability to talk about it convinced my dad something really bad had happened. i learned only a couple months ago that my parents had gone to his house to ask him if he did it. he denied it
column4: but after my parents had left and his dad was no longer listening to the conversation
column5: he called my mom and admitted that it was him. i have no idea what to make of that. it’s still extremely painful to think about. i’m sure it affects my relationships profoundly

column2: aunque años después no recuerde cada detalle
column3: así no sepa como estaba vestido su agresor o el nombre y apellido de cada persona que vio ese día. saben que una de las maneras que tiene nuestro cerebro de protegernos del trauma es justamente hacernos olvidar? por eso aveces hay recuerdos parciales que no por eso dejan de ser reales. reales como las huellas

column1: 327797;instagram;2018-09-29 01:40:28;FALSE;"almost a year ago there was a shift and we called it #metoo and it was both an intense relief and a horror show. when is it the right time to talk about experiences where you were treated as less than human? when is it the right time to stand up so people can tell you to sit back down (and much worse)? i’m still here.

i make decisions every day geared toward protecting myself because i am female. i was taught not to draw attention to myself. i was taught not to 'ask for it' by looking or talking a specific way. i was taught that it was probably my fault when/if anything did/didn't happen. i was taught to judge other females the same way i was taught to judge myself. i was taught that i am accountable for other people's actions. i learned to minimize encounters as 'not that bad/could have been worse'. i learned to trust my gut. i learned to protect myself through avoidance. i still couldn't protect myself from everything. i was taught shame. i was taught to keep my mouth shut. i am still learning how to live in a world where it sometimes feels better if i just lock the door for now. where i try to teach my boys how to treat people well
column2: and with kindness. and that nobody owns the right to touch anyone else's body without consent or even to stand too close to someone in a checkout line and tell them how much prettier they'd be if they'd just smile. i want to smile. experience tells me you might take it the wrong way. #metoo#ibelieveher";;en;#metoo

column1: i had no cognitive ability to even begin to fully understand or realize the abuse inflicted upon me.
i quickly became numb to the pain
column2: because that’s how i learned to cope. it was my mind’s defense mechanism.

column1: i lost count of the days it kept happening. i felt like a used piece of a dirty rag in the filthiest alleyway of the biggest city in the world. all because some pathetic and horrendously sick individuals decided to take advantage of a little girl who was absolutely terrified and who feared for her life if she opened her mouth. the fear was paralyzing.

column2: if we could go back and you could help me as a little girl
column3: would you tell me that what happened to me was okay? that it didn’t happen? that you didn’t believe me? if you’re vehemently shaking your head/saying no to these questions
column5: because there’s no other suitable answer.

column2: not only because i am one
column3: but because their story is valid
column7: and “norm” must absolutely come to a stop. there is no exception.

column5: i realized that even though it is indeed bigger than i am
column6: my story is still an invaluable piece to the puzzle.

column1: 327819;instagram;2018-09-29 01:25:03;FALSE;"i think maybe the reason sexual assault allegations seem to come all at once
column2: one after the other seemingly out of no where
column3: is because women find strength in each other. it may also be because women want their truth to be told
column4: but feel as if their #metoo will blend into the sea of others
column5: allowing them to share the weight of their burden as if it will wash away with the tide. i don't think there is ever a wrong time to share your truth
column6: and sometimes there just isn't a right time. i also know that sometimes
column7: there is a delay in processing confusing sexual experiences. it wasn't until joe and i were married that i was able to identify an experience i had as a teenager for what it was. i had been molested. and it was very confusing because the boy and i liked each other
column8: but i remember saying no repeatedly
column9: and feeling dirty after.  i remember not liking him any more after it happened
column10: and feeling embarrassed when i saw him. i remember the feeling of shame and defeat would ping back into me if i saw him or heard his name. but i never said anything
column11: because i didn't know how to explain it. i never even realized how wrong it was until it affected areas of my marriage. this event had seeped in and settled into the cracks of me
column12: to a point where i didn't realize it wasn't normal. it just became something that happened to me
column13: that i left unspoken so it would go away.

column1: another complication about  coming forward about these things is that
column2: the other person might not remember the experience as you do. if the other person doesn't think they assaulted me
column3: did they? maybe i should have said no
column4: a few more times...will it seem like i'm lying because we liked each other?  if i wasn't  raped..is it really anything to get worked up about? as women
column5: it's almost as if we sympathize with who assaulted us. we don't want to ruin their life
column6: even though their actions have lasting affects on ours. we keep quiet so our experience isn't distorted
column7: and so we can try to keep going as if it didn't happen...

column1: it took a lot to be that
it took a pouring of tearful rain
and a shaking of sleepy earth
she has had to touch the sun
to be the fire she is today
she kept her eyes on the mountains
she heard her voice go up
and wake them to her pain
but she held on to love as a savior

327830;instagram;2018-09-29 01:26:31;FALSE;this morning i called my husband @jimk3.1415 and asked him to set out all of my @dontgiveupsigns for all the women in corvallis who are feeling in need of support. a few hours later he called and asked if i wanted a lawn sign for my birthday that says #metoo on one side and #believewomen on the other.
i said yes. and then @becfreeby made it happen. while she was placing my new birthday sign in the yard this guy ken drove by and becca sent me this message:
when i was installing your sign
column2: a man named ken stopped and made a u-turn to say he stands in support of sisterhood. ❤️😍😭 his name is can opener man on instagram and you have permission to share his image.
don’t give up. keep doing whatever it is you are doing. it is working. for the first time since forever women are holding collective powerful magical space to allow us to rise however we are able.

column1: 327846;instagram;2018-09-29 01:12:34;FALSE;"sometimes during the day i'll catch myself subconsciously grazing a scar on my back. i've been doing this a lot more in the past few months/years alongside the eruption of the #metoo movement
column2: my own growth & most recently dr. ford's amazing bravery shown on live tv.

column1: that scar was put there by an angry
column2: hostile man. one scarily similar to kavanaugh and scarily similar to men we all have dealt with. this world is too full of angry
column3: hostile men escaping consequences for their actions and i'm so sick of it. i'm angry for everyone re-living their trauma. i'm angry for everyone living through it right now. i'm angry for the people who will have to live through it in the future. i'm just really fucking angry. i'm tired of being angry. i'm tired of being at war with myself and wondering how i can suffocate this rage before it suffocates me. i'm not the only one. hell it's felt by mostly everyone at this point.
matter of fact check on everyone you know. let your rage build up. it's okay to be enraged. it's good to feel something powerful rather than numbness. harness it and do something. vote

column2: then you probably know that i’m not a great lover of politics as it is but it greatly disturbs me that politics enter in to someone’s worst day ever. victims seem to have to qualify or prove themselves
column3: to be victims.  sexual crimes take away very personal part of a persons being (sole or what ever you prefer to call it). “why is she saying it now?? why not when it happened?? the one thing you can’t understand is that victims sometimes have to take time
column5: and hopefully someday begin to understand and deal with the trauma of what was inflicted on them. myself
column6: i was 7 years old when i became a victim (for the first time). two teenage boys in my east lou neighborhood physically assaulted me and then sexually assaulted me (i still have a hard time saying that they raped me
column7: but they did). so why now?  why come forward now? think about it
column8: does this make dr. ford more powerful? give her a good name in the political arena? is this fun for her? doubt it. perhaps
column9: she just wants to make sure the the moral integrity of the office is kept. i would do the same thing if i knew my offenders names.

column1: it has never been about the credibility of women.
dr. christine blasey ford withstood an impossible degree of scrutiny to prove to the world that kavanaugh
column2: the man seeking a lifetime appointment in the supreme court (highest court in the land)
column3: had sexually assaulted her in high school.

column1: dr blasey ford is from the same elite society as brett kavanaugh. but it wasn’t enough. to america
column2: her power is only diminished by an unfortunate circumstance of gender. to be ‘credible’ as a woman is still considered less than an untrustworthy

column1: dr. blasey ford has been courageous and despite the disgusting response from the gop and many from the right
column2: she is hailed as a hero among the political left.

law professor anita hill also courageously testified during a supreme court confirmation process. she made it clear that judge clarence thomas had sexually harassed her and acted on her civic duty to tell the truth. anita hill was not considered ‘credible’
column3: nor was she embraced by the political left. she was attacked and vilified across the country. were it not for women like anita hill
column4: we would not have movements like #metoo now.

column1: we must shift our need to sacrifice certain women so that others can be empowered. this isn’t when we give up
column2: it’s when we learn and grow and do things differently.
i have no doubt. but i want to remind y’all that this does not mean we lost the fight. on the contrary
column3: the real fight is just getting started. there will always be men like kavanaugh and his enablers in the pipeline and at the end of it
column5: a powerful force of women to stop them. every time we fight

column1: ugh. i can’t recommend this book.

column2: i’m not a critic by nature. i’ve always had an appreciation for movies
column5: etc because by nature i believe that most things have a purpose for being and are meant to convey a message no matter how enjoyable or well executed.

column1: i felt none of that with this book. if any of you are familiar with james frey he came to fame and notoriety in the early 2000s when his “memoir” a million little pieces was chosen as a selection for oprah’s book club. infamy soon followed when it was revealed that the memoir was a fabricated fiction. i’ve read a million little pieces and his previous novel bright shiny morning and enjoyed both. regardless of the scandal
column2: i found frey to be an interesting writer who’s style evokes an immediacy that i found refreshing. .

column1: cut to 2018. i’m not sure if it’s my tastes that have changed; if it’s the world that it has been written in that has changed; or the fact that frey has lost his poignancy but imho this book is as awful. i finished it in a day because i found frey’s writing style to be like that of a 13 yr old who lacks the vocabulary and emotional maturity to articulate his thoughts. every other sentence contains one of the following: fuck
column7: and pain... sometimes more than once... i’m guessing as a cheap device to denote immediacy and edginess.

column4: immigration... pick your current affairs topic how tone deaf is it to write a story about a no talent
column5: privileged white male travelling through france trying to pursue his dream of being a writer whilst drinking
column7: oh and by the way dating a model (!) still somehow unfulfilled and unhappy with his life...

column1: it’s very rare that i dislike a work of art as much as i disliked this. as much as i appreciated frey’s previous work i found this to be an exercise in masturbatory vanity. sorry... oh well. bring on the next!
ugh. i can’t recommend this book.

column1: cut to 2018. i’m not sure if it’s my tastes that have changed; if it’s the world that it has been written in that has changed; or the fact that frey has lost his poigcy but imho this book is as awful. i finished it in a day because i found frey’s writing style to be like that of a 13 yr old who lacks the vocabulary and emotional maturity to articulate his thoughts. every other sentence contains one of the following: fuck
column7: and pain... sometimes more than once... i’m guessing as a cheap device to denote immediacy and edginess.

column1: 327945;instagram;2018-09-29 00:53:30;FALSE;"a t o: i often paint my body in my performances. if i can touch one person in an audience then i’ve done my job. this performance is about putting war-paint on and preparing oneself to go out in nairobi at night. i call it the mask that nairobi women have to wear and i think it can extend to large parts of the world. but in particular i think of nairobi and what i've been through in my life. from my earliest memories
column3: i remember my dad sexually abusing me. later on when i was about nine-years-old
column4: his brother came to our house one summer to take care of my brother and i. during that visit
column5: he sexually abused me. the memories were hidden deep within and about four years ago
column6: they came to the forefront. i was astounded at the pain that i felt. not talking about it for so many years was really debilitating. being able to let it out through performance is a release. the element of just feeling emotion is there in the performance and i feel that people can connect with me on that level. when a woman is going through something like this
column7: it probably feels like the hardest thing she has been through
column8: but when she comes out on the other side
column9: she will emerge so much stronger. the journey is difficult
column10: but for anyone going through this
column11: i would like you to know that you will emerge as an incredible woman and you have to believe that you are an incredible woman. .

column2: #sb1249 will make it unlawful for cosmetic manufacturers to sell any cosmetic in #california if the final product or any component of the product was tested on animals after january 1

column1: 327986;instagram;2018-09-28 21:21:24;FALSE;"1/4: cont’d in comments👇🦋🌿🌺today i am shopping for native milkweed to plant in my garden. (check seedsource.com #nativeamericanseed & germination guides from @wildflowercenter ) it is one of the best thing you can provide to support your local pollinators’ 🐝🕊🦋especially the monarch butterflies. it’s better than regular ‘tropical butterfly bush’ because the sap in native milkweed has a certain quality that protects them from predators while the other varieties only provide feeding. the tropicals also bloom longer thus interfering with the natural migration cycle
column2: and then the poor little things end up freezing to death because they didn’t make it far enough south!  you might already know that i’m not a big fan of winter
column3: but planting spring bloomers gives me hope. it’s a physical symbolic affirmation that i know there is a light on the other end of this tunnel to come. and after this exhausting week
column4: it’s a nice healthy catharsis too. what are you doing for yourself today? 🌸
